00:02:00.740 --> 00:02:02.520
and does science
actually lead you

00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:07.520
towards that kind of big
T formulation of what

00:02:07.520 --> 00:02:09.199
we know in the world.

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:11.620
And the answer is
kind of humbling.

00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:15.140
So what this is, is an exercise
on how science actually works.

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:18.750
You know, it's what philosophers
like to call epistemology.

00:02:18.750 --> 00:02:22.170
How do we acquire
knowledge of reality?

00:02:22.170 --> 00:02:25.250
And so the first fundamental
point is the following.

00:02:26.610 --> 00:02:29.310
How do we know that you're here?

00:02:29.310 --> 00:02:31.460
How do you know this
is happening right now?

00:02:31.460 --> 00:02:34.820
Well, you know, you have these
amazing sensor apparatus,

00:02:34.820 --> 00:02:35.320
right?

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:37.280
You have your eyes,
and you have your ears

00:02:37.280 --> 00:02:41.500
so your organs are
picking up the information

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:43.130
from the environment, right?

00:02:43.130 --> 00:02:46.240
And they are bringing this
information into your brain.

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:48.470
And your brain is
this amazing thing

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:51.070
that can integrate all
this sensor information

00:02:51.070 --> 00:02:54.590
and construct this
cognitive image

00:02:54.590 --> 00:02:56.920
and impression of
what reality is.

00:02:56.920 --> 00:03:00.280
So what we call reality-- at
least from a more immediate

00:03:00.280 --> 00:03:05.190
way, as humans-- is this sum
total of the sensor integration

00:03:05.190 --> 00:03:07.450
that is happening in
your brain, right?

00:03:07.450 --> 00:03:10.210
And, of course, the point
is that that is really

00:03:10.210 --> 00:03:12.170
not all of reality at all.

00:03:12.170 --> 00:03:14.420
That's just a tiny
little fraction

00:03:14.420 --> 00:03:16.370
of what reality is about.

00:03:16.370 --> 00:03:17.800
And what else is going on?

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:20.050
Well, you know that
right now there

00:03:20.050 --> 00:03:23.810
are tons of electromagnetic
waves going to this room.

00:03:23.810 --> 00:03:28.500
You know, all the FM and AM
radio stations from the areas

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:29.510
around here.

00:03:29.510 --> 00:03:32.720
You have ultraviolet
radiation from these lights.

00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:36.170
You have infrared radiation
that you guys are beaming out,

00:03:36.170 --> 00:03:38.570
because we're all
warm bodies and when

00:03:38.570 --> 00:03:41.390
you're a warm body at about
98 degrees Fahrenheit,

00:03:41.390 --> 00:03:43.330
you're beaming
infrared radiation.

00:03:43.330 --> 00:03:46.020
But all these things
you cannot see.

00:03:46.020 --> 00:03:47.880
But the fact that
you can't see it

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:50.340
doesn't make it
less real, right?

00:03:50.340 --> 00:03:53.340
So in a very concrete
sense, science

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:58.360
is an effort to amplify
the way we see reality.

00:03:58.360 --> 00:03:58.860
Right?

00:03:58.860 --> 00:04:01.730
There's this little line
from "The Little Prince"

00:04:01.730 --> 00:04:03.630
where the fox is talking
to the Little Prince

00:04:03.630 --> 00:04:07.330
and says that what's invisible
is essential to the eye.

00:04:07.330 --> 00:04:09.380
And essentially
science is trying

00:04:09.380 --> 00:04:11.120
to uncover-- at least
modern science-- is

00:04:11.120 --> 00:04:14.360
trying to uncover
this invisible.

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:17.750
Kind of opening our eyes to
what's going on out there.

00:04:17.750 --> 00:04:20.040
So I wanted to kind
of set the mood

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:23.280
with a quote from the master
himself, from Albert Einstein,

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:25.626
and I see there is a
Google equals mc squared

00:04:25.626 --> 00:04:27.000
over there, which
is really cool.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.380
I had to take a picture of
that to show my students.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:33.520
But what he says is the
following, "What I see nature

00:04:33.520 --> 00:04:37.110
is a magnificent structure that
we can comprehend only very

00:04:37.110 --> 00:04:40.340
imperfectly, and that
must fill a thinking

00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:43.170
person with a
feeling of humility."

00:04:43.170 --> 00:04:45.320
And what he is
trying to say there

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:47.240
is almost against
what he believed.

00:04:47.240 --> 00:04:47.740
Right?

00:04:47.740 --> 00:04:50.390
So Einstein was a
realist so he thought

00:04:50.390 --> 00:04:53.820
that there is order in
nature and that there

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:59.200
is some sort of pattern that
we can uncover with our minds.

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:01.440
And it's just a matter
of working hard at it,

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:02.770
and you can figure things out.

00:05:02.770 --> 00:05:04.570
That nature-- as
you probably heard

00:05:04.570 --> 00:05:07.700
before-- he is famous for saying
that God doesn't play dice.

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:09.610
He wasn't talking
about any real God.

00:05:09.610 --> 00:05:12.370
It was meant nature
cannot be random,

00:05:12.370 --> 00:05:14.160
cannot be unpredictable.

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:17.730
There has to be a fundamental
order underneath everything.

00:05:17.730 --> 00:05:21.460
And yet, he also recognized
that as humans we

00:05:21.460 --> 00:05:24.731
can only go so far in
understanding the world.

00:05:24.731 --> 00:05:25.230
Right?

00:05:25.230 --> 00:05:28.870
And so, in that sense, you can
understand things imperfectly,

00:05:28.870 --> 00:05:31.530
and you should have really a
feeling of humility, meaning

00:05:31.530 --> 00:05:33.870
you should be humble to
understand that you really

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:35.171
don't know.

00:05:35.171 --> 00:05:36.670
There's another
quote from Einstein,

00:05:36.670 --> 00:05:38.670
which I think is relevant
in this context, which

00:05:38.670 --> 00:05:39.630
is this one.

00:05:39.630 --> 00:05:42.670
"The first thing we can
experience is the mysterious.

00:05:42.670 --> 00:05:44.410
It is the fundamental
emotion which

00:05:44.410 --> 00:05:47.570
stands at the cradle of
true art and science.

00:05:47.570 --> 00:05:50.300
He who does not know it
and can no longer wonder,

00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:51.970
is as good as dead."

00:05:51.970 --> 00:05:54.330
So basically what he's
saying is, wake up, people.

00:05:54.330 --> 00:05:58.280
There is all this awesome
unknown stuff out there.

00:05:58.280 --> 00:06:00.310
What he calls the
"mystery," what's

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:02.350
out there in nature
that we do not know.

00:06:02.350 --> 00:06:06.136
And if you're not excited by
trying to figure that out,

00:06:06.136 --> 00:06:07.260
then you're just not alive.

00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:07.760
You know?

00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:08.980
That's just not happening.

00:06:08.980 --> 00:06:12.760
And furthermore, it is this
kind of seductive power

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:16.660
that we have to this mystery,
to what we want to figure out,

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:19.710
that is the creative
engine behind so much art

00:06:19.710 --> 00:06:20.990
and so much science.

00:06:20.990 --> 00:06:23.670
So he's bringing this
sort of human urge

00:06:23.670 --> 00:06:26.770
to understand into this
big umbrella, right?

00:06:26.770 --> 00:06:31.030
Putting all our creative output,
be it artistic or scientific,

00:06:31.030 --> 00:06:32.510
under this big
umbrella, which is

00:06:32.510 --> 00:06:34.760
this engagement
with the unknown,

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:38.936
with the mysterious, which is a
very interesting position which

00:06:38.936 --> 00:06:39.435
I share.

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:43.210
And then we have this picture
here of the fish in the bowl.

00:06:43.210 --> 00:06:45.600
so here's the little fish,
and we-- at least when

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:47.760
I look at it, I go, to me
it's a beautiful picture.

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:49.504
But it's also kind
of sad, right?

00:06:49.504 --> 00:06:52.170
Because you look at the fish and
say, poor little guy, you know?

00:06:52.170 --> 00:06:54.690
His universe is so confined.

00:06:54.690 --> 00:06:55.190
Right?

00:06:55.190 --> 00:06:56.430
He is in that little bowl.

00:06:56.430 --> 00:06:57.670
That's all he sees.

00:06:57.670 --> 00:06:59.960
I mean, he can kind of
glimpse through the glass

00:06:59.960 --> 00:07:01.640
and there is some
stuff out there,

00:07:01.640 --> 00:07:03.720
but he can never get to it.

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:05.620
Much better to be the
photographer, right?

00:07:05.620 --> 00:07:08.010
To be the guy on the
outside that can actually

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:11.940
take that picture and see the
sunset and understand that,

00:07:11.940 --> 00:07:15.790
hey, my reality is much
richer than that of the fish.

00:07:15.790 --> 00:07:18.740
And the point I'm going to make
is it's not really, you know?

00:07:18.740 --> 00:07:23.740
That our reality is kind of
exactly like that of the fish.

00:07:23.740 --> 00:07:26.990
And so when we go
conceive the world

00:07:26.990 --> 00:07:28.590
and understand what
is the world like,

00:07:28.590 --> 00:07:32.940
you have to be very
careful to measure where

00:07:32.940 --> 00:07:36.120
you want to take this statement
this is what reality is about.

00:07:36.120 --> 00:07:39.030
There is such a thing
as a fundamental reality

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:40.280
that we try to uncover.

00:07:40.280 --> 00:07:43.030
And I speak to this being a
theoretical physicist that

00:07:43.030 --> 00:07:47.890
works in cosmology and high
energy physics, which is really

00:07:47.890 --> 00:07:50.650
of the big bang and black
holes and Higgs particle.

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:53.610
That's the kind of
stuff I do, and I

00:07:53.610 --> 00:07:56.820
will be happy to answer
questions about that later on.

00:07:56.820 --> 00:08:00.185
But it's important to
understand that when

00:08:00.185 --> 00:08:02.950
we try to push the
boundaries of knowledge,

00:08:02.950 --> 00:08:06.770
we are always going to
hit a certain wall, which

00:08:06.770 --> 00:08:10.820
is the wall of what we can do
to understand what's going on.

00:08:10.820 --> 00:08:14.030
And furthermore-- and
here I quote Heisenberg,

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:16.636
who is one of the architects
of quantum physics--

00:08:16.636 --> 00:08:18.010
he says something
very important.

00:08:18.010 --> 00:08:21.720
He says, "what we observe
is not nature itself

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:25.070
but it's nature exposed to
our method of questioning."

00:08:25.070 --> 00:08:27.960
And that's really interesting,
because what he's telling here

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:31.700
is that there is only a human
way of understanding things.

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:35.150
There is no universal way
of understanding things.

00:08:35.150 --> 00:08:38.809
That kinds of rubs
against our notion

00:08:38.809 --> 00:08:41.750
that there is such a thing
as some universal truth

00:08:41.750 --> 00:08:42.539
out there, right?

00:08:42.539 --> 00:08:45.510
That we should be able
to get to that and that

00:08:45.510 --> 00:08:48.320
is beyond the human frame.

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:54.700
So that if an alien intelligence
can do physics or chemistry,

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:58.160
they are going to come up with
laws of nature which are just

00:08:58.160 --> 00:09:01.290
like our laws of nature, right?

00:09:01.290 --> 00:09:03.270
And what he is saying
here is something

00:09:03.270 --> 00:09:06.832
like, perhaps the content
of those laws is similar,

00:09:06.832 --> 00:09:08.540
but the way they're
going to be expressed

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:09.820
as completely different.

00:09:09.820 --> 00:09:13.140
There is a very human way
of probing reality, right?

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:17.800
That we are animals that
evolved in a very specific set

00:09:17.800 --> 00:09:19.080
of circumstances.

00:09:19.080 --> 00:09:24.600
We have a star, about 150
million miles from us,

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:28.310
and it has a temperature--
a surface temperature--

00:09:28.310 --> 00:09:32.770
of about 6,000 degrees
Celsius, which makes it glow

00:09:32.770 --> 00:09:34.470
white-ish yellow.

00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:38.070
And so any form of
light-- of life, sorry.

00:09:38.070 --> 00:09:41.840
Any form of life that
evolved in this planet

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:45.890
had to maximize the way it
could capture this radiation,

00:09:45.890 --> 00:09:48.950
and hence we and most
of the animals around us

00:09:48.950 --> 00:09:51.160
can see in this
very tiny window all

00:09:51.160 --> 00:09:52.810
of the electromagnetic
spectrum, which

00:09:52.810 --> 00:09:54.400
is what we call
the visible, right?

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:56.870
From the red to
the violet, right?

00:09:56.870 --> 00:10:02.050
And that makes sense, because
if you could see in radio waves

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:04.650
or in microwaves, you know,
when a tiger comes to you,

00:10:04.650 --> 00:10:06.230
you're going to be eaten.

00:10:06.230 --> 00:10:07.740
So it doesn't really
work very well

00:10:07.740 --> 00:10:09.150
from a survival perspective.

00:10:09.150 --> 00:10:13.490
So it's no wonder that our
eyes can capture the most power

00:10:13.490 --> 00:10:16.860
output that the sun can put out.

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:21.130
And so when we try to put
these things in context,

00:10:21.130 --> 00:10:24.890
we want to understand what
is science trying to do.

00:10:24.890 --> 00:10:28.112
And there is this philosopher
from the 17th century, which

00:10:28.112 --> 00:10:30.195
is really an awesome guy,
called Bernard Le Bovier

00:10:30.195 --> 00:10:30.778
de Fontenelle.

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:35.532
So the same year that Newton
published his "Principia,"

00:10:35.532 --> 00:10:37.990
which is the book that changed
the wall, in a sense, right?

00:10:37.990 --> 00:10:41.525
It was the book where the laws
of motion, the law of gravity,

00:10:41.525 --> 00:10:42.025
was written.

00:10:42.025 --> 00:10:45.870
In 1686, this French
philosopher wrote a book

00:10:45.870 --> 00:10:48.865
on the possibility of
life in other planets.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:51.460
And it is a really
interesting book,

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:54.500
because it's constructed as
a dialogue sort of inspired

00:10:54.500 --> 00:10:55.710
by Plato.

00:10:55.710 --> 00:10:59.650
But in that book he
has two characters.

00:10:59.650 --> 00:11:02.200
He has the philosopher,
which is himself,

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:05.650
and a co-protagonist which is a
woman-- who is a woman-- which

00:11:05.650 --> 00:11:09.100
is a very, very rare thing
in the 17th century, who

00:11:09.100 --> 00:11:10.920
is much smarter than
he is in a sense

00:11:10.920 --> 00:11:12.980
that she has this sort wit.

00:11:12.980 --> 00:11:14.680
And there is this
dialogue between them

00:11:14.680 --> 00:11:17.530
in which she is always
questioning his assumptions

00:11:17.530 --> 00:11:19.380
from a natural
philosophical, which

00:11:19.380 --> 00:11:22.599
is the old name for a
science perspective.

00:11:22.599 --> 00:11:24.140
And this guy says
the following, this

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:29.090
is how he summarizes the problem
with trying to figure things

00:11:29.090 --> 00:11:31.420
out from a scientific
perspective, OK?

00:11:31.420 --> 00:11:35.280
So he says, "all philosophy
is based on two things only:

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:37.480
curiosity and poor eyesight."

00:11:37.480 --> 00:11:38.120
Right?

00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:39.536
And I think that's
just brilliant,

00:11:39.536 --> 00:11:41.240
because that is exactly right.

00:11:41.240 --> 00:11:42.690
I mean, we are super curious.

00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:45.580
We want to understand things
the best possible way.

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:46.750
More and more, right?

00:11:46.750 --> 00:11:48.570
More information--
you guys know this

00:11:48.570 --> 00:11:51.230
better than I do how
hungry people are

00:11:51.230 --> 00:11:53.600
all the time for more
and more information.

00:11:53.600 --> 00:11:56.040
And yet, we are myopic, right?

00:11:56.040 --> 00:11:58.730
I mean, there is only so
much we can see, right?

00:11:58.730 --> 00:12:01.990
And there is a tension here
about wanting to know a lot

00:12:01.990 --> 00:12:03.486
and not be able to everything.

00:12:03.486 --> 00:12:08.410
And from this creative tension
comes the output from science,

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:09.640
right?

00:12:09.640 --> 00:12:13.520
So this poor eyesight
also has to do

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:16.310
with our perspective of
what reality is like.

00:12:16.310 --> 00:12:20.770
So now I switch gears and
I go back to 400 years

00:12:20.770 --> 00:12:23.170
or so before Christ
to Plato's cave.

00:12:23.170 --> 00:12:23.670
OK?

00:12:23.670 --> 00:12:28.030
So Plato, in his "Republic"--
in book seven of "Republic"--

00:12:28.030 --> 00:12:30.710
he wrote something called the
allegory of the cave, which

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:36.540
is absolutely a brilliant kind
of way of thinking about what

00:12:36.540 --> 00:12:38.650
is the nature of reality
and how can we know?

00:12:38.650 --> 00:12:39.150
OK?

00:12:39.150 --> 00:12:41.490
And the notion is about
more or less the following.

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:44.500
Let's imagine that we
are inside a cave, OK?

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:47.400
And you guys are the
slaves, because that's

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:48.860
how Plato framed the stuff.

00:12:48.860 --> 00:12:52.700
And the slaves were born
chained in such a way

00:12:52.700 --> 00:12:55.050
that all they could
do is look forward.

00:12:55.050 --> 00:12:55.550
OK?

00:12:55.550 --> 00:12:57.135
So all you could
do is look forward

00:12:57.135 --> 00:13:00.640
to what's being projected on
the cave wall in front of you.

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:01.140
Right?

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:06.130
So for these slaves, reality
was what they could see in there

00:13:06.130 --> 00:13:07.550
and on this cave wall.

00:13:07.550 --> 00:13:08.740
That was reality.

00:13:08.740 --> 00:13:11.425
Now, they didn't know
that behind them there

00:13:11.425 --> 00:13:12.630
was this big, big fire.

00:13:12.630 --> 00:13:15.780
A roaring fire, and a
bunch of philosophers

00:13:15.780 --> 00:13:18.200
are holding stuff up, right?

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:22.310
And the projection-- the
shadows from these objects

00:13:22.310 --> 00:13:25.140
were being projected
on the wall, right?

00:13:25.140 --> 00:13:27.730
And what the slaves saw
was just a projection.

00:13:27.730 --> 00:13:29.560
So they would say,
like, you know, yeah,

00:13:29.560 --> 00:13:31.420
this is like one shape.

00:13:31.420 --> 00:13:34.730
When they have no idea
that the true shape is

00:13:34.730 --> 00:13:36.760
like a rectangle, so to speak.

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:39.960
And so here's a
variation on that

00:13:39.960 --> 00:13:42.320
is when Neo visits
Plato's cave, right?

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:44.280
Neo from "The Matrix," right?

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:47.010
And as you probably know--
if you don't you probably

00:13:47.010 --> 00:13:48.340
couldn't get a job here, right?

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:52.280
So in "The Matrix,"
people thought

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:54.760
they would be seeing
reality, but they

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:56.510
weren't seeing reality, right?

00:13:56.510 --> 00:14:00.260
So here goes Neo
to Plato's cave--

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:03.220
there is Keanu Reeves
with his machine gun--

00:14:03.220 --> 00:14:07.900
and the guy next to him
says, "It is prophesied

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:10.170
that one day a
chosen one among us

00:14:10.170 --> 00:14:12.070
will break free of
this world and reveal

00:14:12.070 --> 00:14:14.040
to us the true
nature of reality."

00:14:14.040 --> 00:14:14.580
Right?

00:14:14.580 --> 00:14:19.720
And he says, "No way." and you
see there the slaves there,

00:14:19.720 --> 00:14:20.330
right?

00:14:20.330 --> 00:14:21.380
And what do they see?

00:14:21.380 --> 00:14:24.170
They see a unicorn
pooping, right?

00:14:24.170 --> 00:14:26.530
And they said, wow,
unicorns exist.

00:14:26.530 --> 00:14:29.250
And they defecate
just like we do.

00:14:29.250 --> 00:14:30.920
And what's really
going on is there

00:14:30.920 --> 00:14:35.090
is that naughty philosopher
behind there making little hand

00:14:35.090 --> 00:14:38.660
signs with his fingers and
projecting these things

00:14:38.660 --> 00:14:42.400
onto the wall totally fooling
the slaves into believing

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:44.230
something that is not real.

00:14:44.230 --> 00:14:44.730
Right?

00:14:44.730 --> 00:14:47.970
So the question is,
OK, who are we here?

00:14:47.970 --> 00:14:50.480
You know, how much can
we see of the world

00:14:50.480 --> 00:14:53.250
and be comfortable with the
notion of reality, right?

00:14:53.250 --> 00:14:57.240
So now we go down to
science, and I broke this

00:14:57.240 --> 00:14:58.660
into three parts.

00:14:58.660 --> 00:15:00.570
So three kinds of realities.

00:15:00.570 --> 00:15:04.240
The cosmic reality of the
universe, material reality,

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:07.140
what is stuff made of,
and cognitive reality.

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:09.480
How do we figure things
out with our minds?

00:15:09.480 --> 00:15:10.060
OK?

00:15:10.060 --> 00:15:14.480
So to set the tone,
let me introduce

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:18.040
to the wonderful things called
scientific instruments that you

00:15:18.040 --> 00:15:20.886
all know about, of course, which
are called reality amplifiers.

00:15:22.070 --> 00:15:23.870
And why do I call them
reality amplifiers?

00:15:23.870 --> 00:15:26.680
Well, because they
reveal invisible worlds.

00:15:26.680 --> 00:15:31.050
Stuff that we cannot see with
our eyes and hear, et cetera.

00:15:31.050 --> 00:15:33.370
And they tell you
things about the world

00:15:33.370 --> 00:15:34.660
that you didn't know before.

00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:38.710
So to give a very specific
example, the microscope.

00:15:38.710 --> 00:15:42.830
So the microscope was invented
in the late 1600s, right?

00:15:42.830 --> 00:15:48.900
Now, the conception of what
life is before the microscope

00:15:48.900 --> 00:15:52.530
and after the microscope is
profoundly different, because

00:15:52.530 --> 00:15:54.460
before the microscope
living things

00:15:54.460 --> 00:15:56.250
were things you
could see, right?

00:15:56.250 --> 00:15:59.530
And after the microscope, you
look into a drop of water,

00:15:59.530 --> 00:16:01.670
and you see all these
"invisible" creatures

00:16:01.670 --> 00:16:02.420
what were alive.

00:16:02.420 --> 00:16:06.455
So all sorts of new questions
like, how small can life be?

00:16:08.630 --> 00:16:11.450
Is there a limit to how
small it can be, and are

00:16:11.450 --> 00:16:13.240
these things related to us?

00:16:13.240 --> 00:16:16.190
And are these things the
things that make us sick?

00:16:16.190 --> 00:16:20.130
So this completely new
way of thinking about life

00:16:20.130 --> 00:16:23.240
emerged from that
single instrument.

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:25.330
The same, obviously,
with the telescope

00:16:25.330 --> 00:16:27.300
and with a bunch of
different detectors.

00:16:27.300 --> 00:16:30.110
I have here on the bottom
two of my favorites.

00:16:30.110 --> 00:16:32.120
So anybody knows what this is?

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:35.950
The Hubble Space
Telescope, right?

00:16:35.950 --> 00:16:39.530
Which is one of the most
amazing machines ever invented.

00:16:39.530 --> 00:16:43.110
Picture this, this is a
robot telescope, right?

00:16:43.110 --> 00:16:47.530
So it's a robotic telescope
that is orbiting very far

00:16:47.530 --> 00:16:48.530
away from earth.

00:16:48.530 --> 00:16:51.350
It is being controlled
by remote control

00:16:51.350 --> 00:16:54.070
here on earth by
astronomers and technicians

00:16:54.070 --> 00:16:57.380
and taking pictures that
have never been taken before,

00:16:57.380 --> 00:16:58.930
and that completely
change the way

00:16:58.930 --> 00:17:01.370
we understand the universe now.

00:17:01.370 --> 00:17:04.849
And on the right-hand
side is the Atlas Detector

00:17:04.849 --> 00:17:07.230
from the Large Hadron
Collider at CERN,

00:17:07.230 --> 00:17:10.390
which is the machine that
discovered that Higgs, right?

00:17:10.390 --> 00:17:12.329
And, I don't know
if you can see this,

00:17:12.329 --> 00:17:14.380
but there is a
little person here.

00:17:14.380 --> 00:17:15.010
It is huge.

00:17:15.010 --> 00:17:16.589
It's four stories high.

00:17:16.589 --> 00:17:20.290
It has more steel than the
whole Eiffel Tower in there.

00:17:20.290 --> 00:17:20.869
OK?

00:17:20.869 --> 00:17:22.940
And that's this
giant thing we used

00:17:22.940 --> 00:17:25.160
to study the smallest
things that exists.

00:17:25.160 --> 00:17:27.410
You know, the
particles of nature.

00:17:27.410 --> 00:17:27.910
OK.

00:17:27.910 --> 00:17:29.090
So cosmic.

00:17:29.090 --> 00:17:31.970
Let me just-- when we're talking
about the nature of reality

00:17:31.970 --> 00:17:34.530
and the nature of
truth, just picture

00:17:34.530 --> 00:17:37.670
the evolution of our
understanding of the universe,

00:17:37.670 --> 00:17:38.170
right?

00:17:38.170 --> 00:17:42.710
So when Columbus got not
quite here, but close to here

00:17:42.710 --> 00:17:47.390
in 1492, what kind of
universe did he believe in?

00:17:47.390 --> 00:17:49.910
They all lived in an
earth-centered universe.

00:17:49.910 --> 00:17:52.480
The earth was static,
it didn't move.

00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:55.590
There was this kind of
verticality to their existence

00:17:55.590 --> 00:17:57.990
in which the earth
was the center,

00:17:57.990 --> 00:18:00.200
then you had all these
planets around it,

00:18:00.200 --> 00:18:02.690
and afterwards you had this
view of the fixed stars.

00:18:02.690 --> 00:18:05.390
And outside all of that
was the realm of God.

00:18:05.390 --> 00:18:09.390
So there was this verticality
in which the universe kind of

00:18:09.390 --> 00:18:12.030
mirrored what
people believed in.

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:16.500
And they guided their
existence based on this,

00:18:16.500 --> 00:18:19.770
and this influenced not
just the way they lived,

00:18:19.770 --> 00:18:21.190
but the way they created things.

00:18:21.190 --> 00:18:24.290
So for example,
Medieval cathedral.

00:18:24.290 --> 00:18:26.162
They are all vertical, right?

00:18:26.162 --> 00:18:27.120
They are all very high.

00:18:27.120 --> 00:18:28.040
Why?

00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:30.040
Well, because as
you go in there,

00:18:30.040 --> 00:18:32.250
you want to look up, right?

00:18:32.250 --> 00:18:33.090
And why?

00:18:33.090 --> 00:18:35.400
Well, because you want to
commune with God up there,

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:35.900
right?

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:39.180
So there was, like, this
reproduction of the macro

00:18:39.180 --> 00:18:41.260
to be human scale
in the cathedrals,

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:42.960
and it was mirrored
in their beliefs.

00:18:44.670 --> 00:18:46.320
So things made sense, right?

00:18:46.320 --> 00:18:48.930
And this is more or less
what Aristotle proposed way

00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:50.830
before the Catholic church.

00:18:50.830 --> 00:18:54.270
But then comes
Copernicus in 1543

00:18:54.270 --> 00:18:58.090
and said, sorry folks, the
earth is just another planet.

00:18:58.090 --> 00:18:59.577
It is nothing special.

00:18:59.577 --> 00:19:01.285
You know, it's just
like Jupiter, Saturn.

00:19:02.430 --> 00:19:04.579
There are eight--
well, at that time

00:19:04.579 --> 00:19:06.870
there wasn't eight because
they only knew until Saturn.

00:19:06.870 --> 00:19:09.650
But there was then Pluto,
and then Pluto is gone.

00:19:09.650 --> 00:19:11.360
Poor guy, right?

00:19:11.360 --> 00:19:14.020
Which actually shows how
shifty science is, right?

00:19:14.020 --> 00:19:16.360
So that's part of how
things evolve, right?

00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:18.190
What we call a
planet has changed

00:19:18.190 --> 00:19:21.670
because we understand planets so
much better than we did before

00:19:21.670 --> 00:19:25.250
that Pluto really
falls out, in a sense.

00:19:25.250 --> 00:19:28.180
But so he shifted
the order of things

00:19:28.180 --> 00:19:31.430
and forced people to
kind of reconsider

00:19:31.430 --> 00:19:33.760
this whole arrangement
that they had before.

00:19:33.760 --> 00:19:35.660
And people were very
confused by this,

00:19:35.660 --> 00:19:38.590
because that centrality
of the earth-- which

00:19:38.590 --> 00:19:39.840
seemed so intuitive, right?

00:19:39.840 --> 00:19:42.105
You walk out, and
you do see the sky is

00:19:42.105 --> 00:19:43.390
turning around us, right?

00:19:43.390 --> 00:19:45.810
I mean, so intuitively
it makes a lot of sense.

00:19:45.810 --> 00:19:49.790
But science is, in
a way, a mechanism

00:19:49.790 --> 00:19:52.470
we have to break with all
these intuitions, which

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:54.230
are false intuitions, right?

00:19:54.230 --> 00:19:56.690
So we can see deeper into
the nature of things.

00:19:56.690 --> 00:19:58.682
And then you cut to
the 20th century,

00:19:58.682 --> 00:20:00.140
and now our picture
of the universe

00:20:00.140 --> 00:20:01.445
is completely different, right?

00:20:01.445 --> 00:20:02.820
This photograph--
which I'm going

00:20:02.820 --> 00:20:07.460
to repeat because it's just one
of the most awesome photographs

00:20:07.460 --> 00:20:09.850
ever taken in history.

00:20:09.850 --> 00:20:12.110
I'm biased, but it's true.

00:20:12.110 --> 00:20:14.110
This is from the
Hubble, and it's

00:20:14.110 --> 00:20:16.899
called the Hubble
Deep Field picture.

00:20:16.899 --> 00:20:17.940
That means the following.

