And we can hardly get to Mar.

00:20:44.300 --> 00:20:46.690
So it's a long way, folks,
to get out of the Milky Way.

00:20:46.690 --> 00:20:47.580
But still.

00:20:47.580 --> 00:20:50.209
So you have galaxies
here, and then

00:20:50.209 --> 00:20:52.000
you say, oh, what about
these little stars?

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:53.100
Well, these are not stars.

00:20:53.100 --> 00:20:54.530
They are galaxies, too.

00:20:54.530 --> 00:20:56.720
They're just
further away, right?

00:20:56.720 --> 00:21:00.610
So each point of light
here is a galaxy as

00:21:00.610 --> 00:21:03.430
big as these big spirals,
which are closer.

00:21:03.430 --> 00:21:06.140
And each one of these galaxies
have about 200 billion,

00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:09.460
100 billion stars, just like
our Milky Way does, right?

00:21:09.460 --> 00:21:11.451
So we live in the Milky
Way-- just to give you

00:21:11.451 --> 00:21:13.580
a little bit of
perspective here--

00:21:13.580 --> 00:21:18.050
which is this big mass of stars,
about 200 billion of them.

00:21:18.050 --> 00:21:21.400
The sun is one, and the sun
has eight planets, right?

00:21:22.845 --> 00:21:24.220
And when you look
at the planets,

00:21:24.220 --> 00:21:26.380
you say, OK, that's
not the whole story.

00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:28.120
Because planets have moons.

00:21:28.120 --> 00:21:31.250
So Jupiter, for example,
has over 60 moons.

00:21:31.250 --> 00:21:33.320
So nighttime on
Jupiter must be just

00:21:33.320 --> 00:21:35.420
awesome to look at these moons.

00:21:35.420 --> 00:21:38.350
And that tells you that
in our galaxy alone

00:21:38.350 --> 00:21:40.870
there are trillions
of different worlds.

00:21:40.870 --> 00:21:42.880
There are trillions of
worlds, and they're all

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:44.680
completely different
from one another.

00:21:44.680 --> 00:21:46.430
They may be somewhat
similar in some ways,

00:21:46.430 --> 00:21:49.420
but there are no two
identical worlds.

00:21:49.420 --> 00:21:51.600
And then you look at this
and say, damn, you know,

00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:53.660
each each one of these
things is a galaxy.

00:21:53.660 --> 00:21:56.390
Each one of these galaxies
has these billions of stars.

00:21:56.390 --> 00:22:00.270
And so the numbers are
ridiculously staggering, right?

00:22:00.270 --> 00:22:03.490
And how do we gather
information from this?

00:22:03.490 --> 00:22:05.240
Well, from light, right?

00:22:05.240 --> 00:22:08.730
And so, for example, when
you look at the moon,

00:22:08.730 --> 00:22:11.990
you're seeing the
moon 1.2 seconds ago,

00:22:11.990 --> 00:22:14.300
because that's how long light
takes to go from the moon

00:22:14.300 --> 00:22:15.060
to us.

00:22:15.060 --> 00:22:17.525
When you're looking at the
sun, it's about eight minutes.

00:22:17.525 --> 00:22:21.000
It takes about eight minutes
for light to travel to us.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:23.780
As you know, the speed
of light is 186,000 miles

00:22:23.780 --> 00:22:27.180
in a second, which is
another ridiculous number.

00:22:27.180 --> 00:22:30.010
Basically it means something
like, if you blink your eye,

00:22:30.010 --> 00:22:32.830
light goes 7 and 1/2
times around the earth.

00:22:32.830 --> 00:22:35.550
So blink your eyes, 7 and
1/2 times around the earth.

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:39.120
And it takes eight minutes for
it to come from the sun to us.

00:22:39.120 --> 00:22:43.280
And it takes 2 million years for
light to come from the closest

00:22:43.280 --> 00:22:46.440
this galaxy, which
is Andromeda, to us.

00:22:46.440 --> 00:22:50.480
So when somebody points a
telescope and sees Andromeda,

00:22:50.480 --> 00:22:54.140
he or she is seeing Andromeda
as it was 2 million years ago.

00:22:54.140 --> 00:22:56.570
Meaning when our
ancestors were beginning

00:22:56.570 --> 00:22:58.890
to go bipedal in Africa, right?

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:01.577
That's when that
light left Andromeda.

00:23:01.577 --> 00:23:03.910
So what that tells you is
that when you look at the sky,

00:23:03.910 --> 00:23:05.790
you're looking at the past.

00:23:05.790 --> 00:23:10.200
The sky's our giant time
machine looking at the past.

00:23:10.200 --> 00:23:14.240
And parenthesis here, actually
you are seeing me in the past

00:23:14.240 --> 00:23:14.740
as well.

00:23:14.740 --> 00:23:18.450
You see me about one billionth
of a second ago, right?

00:23:18.450 --> 00:23:20.250
Because that's how
long light takes

00:23:20.250 --> 00:23:22.752
to travel some of this
distance, which basically means

00:23:22.752 --> 00:23:24.085
that the present does not exist.

00:23:25.100 --> 00:23:28.970
Now is a cognitive fabrication,
because every information

00:23:28.970 --> 00:23:31.750
we gather takes time
to get to us, right?

00:23:31.750 --> 00:23:35.090
And what happens though is
the light is so fast compared

00:23:35.090 --> 00:23:38.300
to how fast our
brain can process

00:23:38.300 --> 00:23:41.100
this information that it seems
that everything is integrated

00:23:41.100 --> 00:23:44.850
into an instant, but it really
is not in an instant, you know?

00:23:44.850 --> 00:23:46.680
So that's something to ponder.

00:23:47.900 --> 00:23:49.300
So what does that tell you?

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:52.320
Well, we now know that the
universe is not just this,

00:23:52.320 --> 00:23:54.105
but is actually expanding.

00:23:54.105 --> 00:23:57.710
The universe is a
dynamic entity so when

00:23:57.710 --> 00:23:59.479
people talk about the
expanding universe,

00:23:59.479 --> 00:24:01.520
they always imagine that
there was this big bang,

00:24:01.520 --> 00:24:04.500
there was a bomb that exploded
at the beginning of everything

00:24:04.500 --> 00:24:07.210
and the galaxies are sort
of like shrapnel moving out.

00:24:07.210 --> 00:24:08.760
That is completely wrong.

00:24:08.760 --> 00:24:11.180
That is really not what the
expansion of the universe

00:24:11.180 --> 00:24:11.986
is at all.

00:24:11.986 --> 00:24:13.610
The expansion of the
universe is really

00:24:13.610 --> 00:24:16.580
an expansion of the
fabric of space itself.

00:24:16.580 --> 00:24:20.110
It's sort of like if
the floor underneath

00:24:20.110 --> 00:24:22.080
was made of rubber, OK?

00:24:22.080 --> 00:24:24.810
And I pushed a button here,
and as I pushed the button,

00:24:24.810 --> 00:24:27.355
it started stretching into
two dimensional directions.

00:24:27.355 --> 00:24:29.080
You have two directions here.

00:24:29.080 --> 00:24:31.876
And you'd see everybody moving
away from you, you know?

00:24:31.876 --> 00:24:34.237
You'd look around and
say, hey, man, look.

00:24:34.237 --> 00:24:35.570
Everybody's moving away from me.

00:24:35.570 --> 00:24:37.940
I am the center of
the universe, right?

00:24:37.940 --> 00:24:39.950
And the person next
to says, sorry, dude.

00:24:39.950 --> 00:24:41.750
I am also seeing
everybody moving away

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:43.820
from me so I am the center.

00:24:43.820 --> 00:24:45.870
Because there is no center.

00:24:45.870 --> 00:24:48.710
This is an expansion
of space itself

00:24:48.710 --> 00:24:51.380
that is stretching outwards
and the galaxies are basically

00:24:51.380 --> 00:24:55.110
being taken with, sort of
like a cork floating on water,

00:24:55.110 --> 00:24:56.750
you know, in a river, right?

00:24:56.750 --> 00:24:59.300
So that's really
what's going on.

00:24:59.300 --> 00:25:02.490
And so we now know
that this expansion

00:25:02.490 --> 00:25:06.860
has been going for about 14
billion years-- well, 13.8

00:25:06.860 --> 00:25:08.110
billion years.

00:25:08.110 --> 00:25:09.840
Now, you put these
two things together,

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:15.070
that light takes time to get to
and that the expansion started

00:25:15.070 --> 00:25:17.770
in a finite time ago,
and that tells you

00:25:17.770 --> 00:25:22.280
that light could only travel
so far within that time.

00:25:22.280 --> 00:25:26.010
And that tells you that
you can only see stuff up

00:25:26.010 --> 00:25:27.055
to a certain boundary.

00:25:27.055 --> 00:25:28.889
We call it the horizon.

00:25:28.889 --> 00:25:30.680
Just sort of like when
you go to the beach,

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:32.990
you know, there is
the horizon there

00:25:32.990 --> 00:25:35.260
where the ocean hits
this sky, right?

00:25:35.260 --> 00:25:37.810
And you know that the
ocean doesn't end there,

00:25:37.810 --> 00:25:39.549
but that's as far
as you can see.

00:25:39.549 --> 00:25:40.590
That's very nice similar.

00:25:40.590 --> 00:25:45.740
In cosmology we have this light
bubble-- the fish in the bowl--

00:25:45.740 --> 00:25:48.170
and we are inside
this light bubble.

00:25:48.170 --> 00:25:51.220
And there may be more universe
out there-- probably there is.

00:25:51.220 --> 00:25:53.350
People talk about
multiverses right now,

00:25:53.350 --> 00:25:55.760
which is something that you
may want to ask me-- hint,

00:25:55.760 --> 00:25:57.280
hint-- about.

00:25:57.280 --> 00:26:00.260
But you cannot see it.

00:26:00.260 --> 00:26:03.910
So it's something that
is not just unknown,

00:26:03.910 --> 00:26:06.510
it's unknowable, right?

00:26:06.510 --> 00:26:09.320
Which is like, wow, so
science is telling us there

00:26:09.320 --> 00:26:12.500
are things which are not
just we will figure them out?

00:26:12.500 --> 00:26:16.760
We cannot figure them out unless
you come up with a new physics

00:26:16.760 --> 00:26:19.017
that says that the speed
of light is not the limit,

00:26:19.017 --> 00:26:20.850
and then, you know, all
bets are off, right?

00:26:20.850 --> 00:26:22.070
Then you can say anything.

00:26:22.070 --> 00:26:25.130
When you break the conceptual
structure of something,

00:26:25.130 --> 00:26:26.880
everything can go.

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:30.070
So there is your first
unknowable at the cosmic scale,

00:26:30.070 --> 00:26:30.590
right?

00:26:30.590 --> 00:26:33.180
That we really live in
a bubble of information,

00:26:33.180 --> 00:26:36.900
which is the cosmic horizon,
and we cannot see directly

00:26:36.900 --> 00:26:38.540
what's going on out there.

00:26:38.540 --> 00:26:39.040
OK?

00:26:40.321 --> 00:26:40.820
OK.

00:26:40.820 --> 00:26:43.260
Now, just talk about material.

00:26:43.260 --> 00:26:46.380
So what is the world made of?

00:26:46.380 --> 00:26:48.280
This stuff, right,
that we are made of?

00:26:48.280 --> 00:26:51.700
So we are obviously
made of atoms, right?

00:26:51.700 --> 00:26:55.560
And you know that atoms are
made of protons, electrons,

00:26:55.560 --> 00:26:56.300
and neutrons.

00:26:56.300 --> 00:27:00.000
Where would computers be without
the electrons flowing around,

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:00.600
right?

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:04.620
And that stuff, this
stuff that we are made of,

00:27:04.620 --> 00:27:07.970
and we have about
92 stable chemical

00:27:07.970 --> 00:27:11.870
elements that we have found
and that exist, everything else

00:27:11.870 --> 00:27:13.170
is unstable.

00:27:13.170 --> 00:27:16.430
And all of these things
came from stars, right?

00:27:16.430 --> 00:27:19.521
So when you ask where did the
chemistry of the universe come

00:27:19.521 --> 00:27:20.020
from?

00:27:20.020 --> 00:27:24.260
Where is the calcium and
the iron that makes me?

00:27:24.260 --> 00:27:25.780
Where does that stuff come from?

00:27:25.780 --> 00:27:28.880
It came from stars that
exploded a very long time ago

00:27:28.880 --> 00:27:33.580
before the solar system formed
in about 4.5 billion years.

00:27:33.580 --> 00:27:36.550
And so when people
say we are stardust,

00:27:36.550 --> 00:27:38.010
that is absolutely correct.

00:27:38.010 --> 00:27:39.820
We really are
literally stardust.

00:27:41.650 --> 00:27:45.310
And so we are part of this cycle
of creation and destruction

00:27:45.310 --> 00:27:50.050
where matter becomes recycled
from hydrogen into everything

00:27:50.050 --> 00:27:51.904
else, you know?

00:27:51.904 --> 00:27:53.320
One astronomer
once said something

00:27:53.320 --> 00:27:55.260
that I really like
which is like, people

00:27:55.260 --> 00:27:58.840
is what happens to hydrogen
when you wait long enough.

00:27:58.840 --> 00:28:00.140
Which is exactly right.

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:02.120
You know, it takes a
long time for hydrogen

00:28:02.120 --> 00:28:04.070
to be processed into
the heavier elements,

00:28:04.070 --> 00:28:06.410
and then obviously
for life to develop

00:28:06.410 --> 00:28:09.610
from that primal,
fundamental substance.

00:28:09.610 --> 00:28:13.380
But it turns out that, you
know, this stuff-- the electrons

00:28:13.380 --> 00:28:16.640
and protons-- make up
5% of the universe.

00:28:17.810 --> 00:28:21.180
The rest we don't
know what it is.

00:28:21.180 --> 00:28:21.680
OK?

00:28:21.680 --> 00:28:22.680
We know it's there.

00:28:22.680 --> 00:28:24.984
It's sort of like you're
going to make a cake,

00:28:24.984 --> 00:28:27.150
and it tells you, look,
there are three ingredients.

00:28:27.150 --> 00:28:30.470
I know that water is one
of them, and it's about 5%.

00:28:30.470 --> 00:28:32.010
And there are two others.

00:28:32.010 --> 00:28:35.930
And one is about 23
the other is about 73,

00:28:35.930 --> 00:28:37.390
but I don't know what they are.

00:28:37.390 --> 00:28:38.290
So figure it out.

00:28:38.290 --> 00:28:39.790
How are you going
to make that cake?

00:28:39.790 --> 00:28:43.500
That is how we are picturing
the cosmos today, you know?

00:28:43.500 --> 00:28:46.000
So these two items
mystery ingredients

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:48.420
are called dark matter
and dark energy.

00:28:48.420 --> 00:28:51.260
And dark matter is
most probably made

00:28:51.260 --> 00:28:56.960
of particles that have mass
but have nothing to do with us.

00:28:56.960 --> 00:28:58.775
Like protons,
electrons, or if you

00:28:58.775 --> 00:29:00.620
want to go deeper
into particle physics

00:29:00.620 --> 00:29:02.430
quarks or Higgs or
anything like that.

00:29:02.430 --> 00:29:05.470
They are something
else, and they sort out

00:29:05.470 --> 00:29:07.140
float around, gravitationally.

00:29:07.140 --> 00:29:10.150
They are sort of like a
cloak around the galaxies.

00:29:10.150 --> 00:29:13.050
And they are in a
factor of one to five.

00:29:13.050 --> 00:29:14.950
So they are five
times more abundant

00:29:14.950 --> 00:29:17.590
than our stuff in galaxies.

00:29:17.590 --> 00:29:19.920
And people have
been trying to catch

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:22.560
these guys for
about three decades.

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:24.280
And we haven't been
able to do that.

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:27.620
Actually, at Berkley
there is a very big group

00:29:27.620 --> 00:29:29.690
that has been
trying to get these.

00:29:29.690 --> 00:29:31.610
And you can't,
because right now,

00:29:31.610 --> 00:29:34.130
if dark matter has
really made a particles,

00:29:34.130 --> 00:29:35.720
they are going through us.

00:29:35.720 --> 00:29:36.890
You know?

00:29:36.890 --> 00:29:39.900
They interact so weakly with
us that we don't even know.

00:29:39.900 --> 00:29:42.200
Just like there is natural
radioactivity going

00:29:42.200 --> 00:29:44.620
from the ground going
through you right now.

00:29:44.620 --> 00:29:48.400
And even more
spectacularly, the sun,

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:51.470
to fuse hydrogen
into helium, produces

00:29:51.470 --> 00:29:52.920
particles called
neutrinos, right?

00:29:52.920 --> 00:29:54.600
Which are called the
"ghost particles."

00:29:54.600 --> 00:29:56.170
They go almost
through everything.

00:29:56.170 --> 00:30:00.355
And right now, per second, there
are about one trillion-- one

00:30:00.355 --> 00:30:03.050
trillion-- neutrinos going
through you per second, right?

00:30:04.145 --> 00:30:05.250
And we have no idea.

00:30:05.250 --> 00:30:07.670
So there is this
shower of stuff that

00:30:07.670 --> 00:30:11.690
is invisible, but
yet very real, right?

00:30:11.690 --> 00:30:14.060
Anyway, so we don't know
what the dark matter is yet.

00:30:14.060 --> 00:30:15.410
There are many possibilities.

00:30:16.740 --> 00:30:18.595
Fancy names,
supersymmetric particles.

00:30:20.640 --> 00:30:22.069
But we are not quite sure.

00:30:22.069 --> 00:30:23.610
And then there is
the big guy, right?

00:30:23.610 --> 00:30:28.820
The 73%, the dark energy, which
was a complete surprise that

00:30:28.820 --> 00:30:32.190
came in 1998, which was
one of these discoveries

00:30:32.190 --> 00:30:34.740
that everybody was
praying to be wrong.

00:30:34.740 --> 00:30:36.600
Please go away.

00:30:36.600 --> 00:30:40.660
Because it is so weird
and so mysterious, really.

00:30:40.660 --> 00:30:44.560
Basically it says not just that
the galaxies are moving away

00:30:44.560 --> 00:30:47.710
from one another, but about
five billion years ago they

00:30:47.710 --> 00:30:50.150
start accelerating
away from one another.

00:30:50.150 --> 00:30:53.950
Sort of like if there is some
kind of repulsive force pushing

00:30:53.950 --> 00:30:58.660
space apart and taking
these galaxies with, OK?

00:30:58.660 --> 00:31:00.350
Now, what could do that?

00:31:00.350 --> 00:31:01.770
Well, there are
candidates, right?

00:31:01.770 --> 00:31:04.835
Einstein himself put a
term in his equations

00:31:04.835 --> 00:31:10.620
in 1917 where you can put
a term in the equations

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:11.630
that kind of does that.

00:31:11.630 --> 00:31:13.830
It induces this kind
of stretching of space,

00:31:13.830 --> 00:31:15.940
it's called the cosmological
constant, right?

00:31:17.040 --> 00:31:20.330
But he abandoned it
afterwards saying

00:31:20.330 --> 00:31:22.090
that was just very ugly stuff.

00:31:22.090 --> 00:31:23.750
He called it, "my
biggest blunder."

00:31:23.750 --> 00:31:28.230
And lo and behold, here the
thing is, again, sort of.

00:31:28.230 --> 00:31:29.530
Or it could be something else.

00:31:29.530 --> 00:31:31.380
Something like an aether.

00:31:31.380 --> 00:31:34.860
I don't know if you guys
remember, in the 19th century

00:31:34.860 --> 00:31:36.630
people believed
that light traveled

00:31:36.630 --> 00:31:38.390
in some sort of
mysterious medium

00:31:38.390 --> 00:31:40.120
called the aether, right?

00:31:40.120 --> 00:31:41.400
And everybody believed that.

00:31:41.400 --> 00:31:43.150
And the aether was
just the weirdest thing

00:31:43.150 --> 00:31:44.220
you can possibly imagine.

00:31:44.220 --> 00:31:47.340
Transparent,
weightless, and yet more

00:31:47.340 --> 00:31:50.930
dense than steel in order
to be able to transfer waves

00:31:50.930 --> 00:31:55.180
that fast, at the
speed of light.

00:31:55.180 --> 00:31:57.990
And people believed that
stuff because they could not

00:31:57.990 --> 00:32:01.530
imagine that a wave could travel
in an empty space, in a vacuum,

00:32:01.530 --> 00:32:02.030
right?

00:32:03.140 --> 00:32:05.795
And there goes dark
energy, and it sort of

00:32:05.795 --> 00:32:06.670
looks like an aether.

00:32:06.670 --> 00:32:09.470
It is sort of-- the same way
the air is everywhere here,

00:32:09.470 --> 00:32:12.320
there is this thing
across the space that

00:32:12.320 --> 00:32:17.240
is filling up universe making
it move outwards really fast.

00:32:17.240 --> 00:32:20.690
So fast that if
nothing reverses this,

00:32:20.690 --> 00:32:25.670
in about a long time--
50 billion years

00:32:25.670 --> 00:32:28.260
or so, so way ahead
of time-- the universe

00:32:28.260 --> 00:32:31.090
is going to look completely
different than it does now.

00:32:31.090 --> 00:32:34.950
So if the astronomers of
50 billion years from now--

00:32:34.950 --> 00:32:37.500
we can go talk about that later.

00:32:37.500 --> 00:32:40.329
That's a whole other talk--
but assuming that they're there

00:32:40.329 --> 00:32:41.870
and they are looking
at the universe,

00:32:41.870 --> 00:32:43.786
they would see something
completely different.

00:32:43.786 --> 00:32:45.980
They would see almost
complete darkness,

00:32:45.980 --> 00:32:47.730
because the galaxies
would be just so far

00:32:47.730 --> 00:32:50.890
out that the light could
not reach us anymore.

00:32:50.890 --> 00:32:54.160
So they would be sort of in
an island universe, you know?

00:32:54.160 --> 00:32:56.170
And not be able to see
anything out there.

00:32:56.170 --> 00:33:00.100
So the way you picture the
universe changes completely

00:33:00.100 --> 00:33:01.330
as we advance in time.

00:33:02.740 --> 00:33:04.580
Let me just make a
note of what this is.

00:33:04.580 --> 00:33:09.180
So this is a self-portrait by
Rembrandt, the Dutch painter.

00:33:09.180 --> 00:33:13.450
And if you have seen any other
one of his self-portraits,

00:33:13.450 --> 00:33:15.190
they are always kind of gloomy.

00:33:15.190 --> 00:33:17.520
But this one he did
when he was young,

00:33:17.520 --> 00:33:22.110
and it's called Self-portrait
in the Likeness of Democritus.

00:33:22.110 --> 00:33:25.390
Now, Democritus
was the second guy

00:33:25.390 --> 00:33:28.400
that came up with the
notion of atomism, right?

00:33:28.400 --> 00:33:30.630
That particles are made
of little bits, right?

00:33:30.630 --> 00:33:34.470
That you can break matter
into fundamental little bits.

00:33:34.470 --> 00:33:38.370
And he was also called the
Laughing Philosopher, hence

00:33:38.370 --> 00:33:39.630
the laughing Rembrandt there.

00:33:39.630 --> 00:33:42.140
And the reason why he was
called the Laughing Philosopher

00:33:42.140 --> 00:33:45.390
is because he believed
that only if you

00:33:45.390 --> 00:33:48.620
develop your faculty
of critical thinking

00:33:48.620 --> 00:33:53.710
and free yourself from slavery--
the slavery of superstitious

00:33:53.710 --> 00:33:56.980
belief-- can you
truly be happy, right?

00:33:56.980 --> 00:34:01.350
And he, of course, reached his
rational nirvana, in a sense.

00:34:01.350 --> 00:34:03.880
And he was a happy guy, and
that was his nickname, right?

00:34:03.880 --> 00:34:06.870
So he was very much
anti-religious belief,

00:34:06.870 --> 00:34:07.370
you know.

00:34:07.370 --> 00:34:11.870
And in fact, Lucretius, when
he wrote his famous poem

00:34:11.870 --> 00:34:15.540
about the atomistic
structure of nature,

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:19.730
he would use this image in
exactly in the same way.

00:34:19.730 --> 00:34:24.150
That to be able to think
critically about reality

00:34:24.150 --> 00:34:26.500
is your way to break
free of slavery

00:34:26.500 --> 00:34:28.989
from superstition, right?

00:34:28.989 --> 00:34:32.780
It's better not to know
than to live like a fool

00:34:32.780 --> 00:34:35.184
or be fooled by
belief so to speak.

00:34:35.184 --> 00:34:37.980
Anyway so of course
when we go and talk

00:34:37.980 --> 00:34:40.860
about what we understand of
matter now at the quantum

00:34:40.860 --> 00:34:44.560
level, there are all sorts
of technical questions

00:34:44.560 --> 00:34:47.110
that we have to ask
which are really strange.

00:34:47.110 --> 00:34:51.130
So we, here, live in
our "classical" reality

00:34:51.130 --> 00:34:52.915
where we can touch
things and there

00:34:52.915 --> 00:34:55.540
is an objective
separation between us

00:34:55.540 --> 00:34:56.730
and everything else, right?

00:34:56.730 --> 00:34:58.680
You know you have a
chair outside of you.

00:34:58.680 --> 00:34:59.880
You're sitting on it.

00:34:59.880 --> 00:35:01.280
When you go to
the quantum world,

00:35:01.280 --> 00:35:04.490
when you look at electrons
and your study them,

00:35:04.490 --> 00:35:06.310
everything goes down the drain.

00:35:06.310 --> 00:35:09.780
First because you don't
see an electron, right?

00:35:09.780 --> 00:35:11.400
You don't see a
fundamental particle.

00:35:11.400 --> 00:35:15.150
What you do see is a click
in a detector, right?

00:35:15.150 --> 00:35:17.620
Or a little curve in a detector.

00:35:17.620 --> 00:35:22.270
And that thing appeared there
after being amplified a lot

00:35:22.270 --> 00:35:23.710
by these photo multipliers.

00:35:23.710 --> 00:35:26.320
So the electron,
whatever that is,

00:35:26.320 --> 00:35:31.360
creates some sort of transfer
of energy and momentum.

00:35:31.360 --> 00:35:34.460
And this thing is
amplified, and then it

00:35:34.460 --> 00:35:36.320
becomes a click that we see.

00:35:36.320 --> 00:35:41.040
There is a huge gap between
the reality of that electron

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:45.280
and our reality of looking
at data on a computer screen,

00:35:45.280 --> 00:35:45.950
right?

00:35:45.950 --> 00:35:50.750
And so there is no immediate
connection with the very small,

00:35:50.750 --> 00:35:52.260
so to speak.

00:35:52.260 --> 00:35:54.210
And so when you look
at the equations

00:35:54.210 --> 00:35:56.360
that describes these
things, and they were all

00:35:56.360 --> 00:35:59.470
developed to kind of
make sense of data.

00:35:59.470 --> 00:36:01.440
I mean, people were
making experiments

00:36:01.440 --> 00:36:04.005
with electrons and
fundamental particles that

00:36:04.005 --> 00:36:06.780
were very strange and
caused a lot of distress.

00:36:06.780 --> 00:36:07.970
Including Einstein, right?

00:36:07.970 --> 00:36:11.040
Because what was apparent
is that you could not

00:36:11.040 --> 00:36:14.360
have a deterministic way of
thinking about reality anymore.

00:36:14.360 --> 00:36:16.350
Everything was
really probabilistic.

00:36:16.350 --> 00:36:20.230
So the equations would say,
look, an electron could be here

00:36:20.230 --> 00:36:22.900
or could be there with
a certain probability

00:36:22.900 --> 00:36:24.830
after you measure it.

00:36:24.830 --> 00:36:27.450
Before, if you
take it literally,

00:36:27.450 --> 00:36:29.410
the physics of
quantum mechanics,

00:36:29.410 --> 00:36:31.490
you can't even say
an electron exists

00:36:31.490 --> 00:36:34.620
until it interacts
with a detector, right?

00:36:34.620 --> 00:36:37.560
So that brings this interesting
philosophical question, which

00:36:37.560 --> 00:36:42.260
is, hey, if the electron only
exists when I interact with it,

00:36:42.260 --> 00:36:46.541
I am creating reality by the
way I interact with reality.

00:36:46.541 --> 00:36:47.040
Right?

00:36:47.040 --> 00:36:51.860
So is reality dependent on us,
like an intelligent observer,

00:36:51.860 --> 00:36:54.860
or is it just the detector
that is creating the reality?

00:36:54.860 --> 00:36:58.040
There are all sorts of weird,
complicated philosophical

00:36:58.040 --> 00:37:00.870
questions that I go into a
lot of detail in the book,

00:37:00.870 --> 00:37:03.260
I can't in 40
minutes, obviously.

00:37:03.260 --> 00:37:08.240
But the interesting point here
is that in quantum physics

00:37:08.240 --> 00:37:13.700
you have this deep connection
between the way we study

00:37:13.700 --> 00:37:17.730
reality and the way that reality
manifests itself as opposed

00:37:17.730 --> 00:37:20.260
to this separation
that you see a rainbow,

00:37:20.260 --> 00:37:21.200
there is the rainbow.

00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:21.720
Right?

00:37:21.720 --> 00:37:24.400
And with the electron, you
can see an electron as a wave

00:37:24.400 --> 00:37:27.430
or as a particle depending
how you set up the experiment

00:37:27.430 --> 00:37:29.090
to study an electron.

00:37:29.090 --> 00:37:30.010
So what is it?

00:37:30.010 --> 00:37:30.720
Is it a wave?

00:37:30.720 --> 00:37:31.530
Is it a particle?

00:37:31.530 --> 00:37:33.435
And this sort of like
an endless debate

00:37:33.435 --> 00:37:35.560
which has to do with this
interpretation of quantum

00:37:35.560 --> 00:37:36.450
mechanics.

00:37:36.450 --> 00:37:39.090
On the other hand, it is
the most successful theory

00:37:39.090 --> 00:37:41.500
we have in physics, right?

00:37:41.500 --> 00:37:45.360
It is when you make measurements
with quantum mechanics,

00:37:45.360 --> 00:37:48.190
you get a precision
to 12 decimal points.

00:37:48.190 --> 00:37:49.990
There is no theory
that can do that.

00:37:49.990 --> 00:37:54.080
I mean, gravity sucks compared
to that in terms of precision.

00:37:54.080 --> 00:37:57.330
And it's much older
than quantum mechanics.

00:37:57.330 --> 00:38:00.240
But when we interpret quantum
mechanics, the whole notion

00:38:00.240 --> 00:38:03.690
of how deep can
you go into reality

00:38:03.690 --> 00:38:05.550
becomes very convoluted.

00:38:05.550 --> 00:38:09.960
And essentially also the fact
that there isn't a fundamental

00:38:09.960 --> 00:38:14.100
randomness to the way these
particles behave that we cannot

00:38:14.100 --> 00:38:14.670
predict.

00:38:14.670 --> 00:38:18.530
So you cannot come up with
a theory that describes

00:38:18.530 --> 00:38:21.750
if an electron that you're going
to measure is going to spin

00:38:21.750 --> 00:38:24.450
this way or that way
when you detect it.

00:38:24.450 --> 00:38:27.750
So to make it simple, let's say
the electron can do two things:

00:38:27.750 --> 00:38:30.810
go counterclockwise
and clockwise, right?

00:38:30.810 --> 00:38:33.340
So we have 50%
probability of when

00:38:33.340 --> 00:38:36.399
you detect it being this
way or the other way.

00:38:36.399 --> 00:38:38.440
And when you detect it,
you're going to find out.

00:38:38.440 --> 00:38:43.070
But you cannot do the
theory to predict that.

00:38:43.070 --> 00:38:46.620
So there is a
fundamental unknowability

00:38:46.620 --> 00:38:48.150
at the very core of matter.

00:38:48.150 --> 00:38:50.870
So you go from the edge of the
universe, that we cannot know,

00:38:50.870 --> 00:38:55.140
to the very core of matter, that
we also cannot know with this

00:38:55.140 --> 00:38:57.000
precision that we want, right?

00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:00.030
So these are two sort of
very interesting unknowables.

00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:02.910
And they don't seem
to be going away.

00:39:02.910 --> 00:39:05.222
In particular, in the
case of quantum physics,

00:39:05.222 --> 00:39:06.680
I was really upset
that they didn't

00:39:06.680 --> 00:39:08.105
get the Nobel Prize this year.

00:39:08.105 --> 00:39:09.480
They gave the
Nobel Prize to guys

00:39:09.480 --> 00:39:12.670
who developed the LED,
which is fair enough, right?

00:39:12.670 --> 00:39:14.550
Very important, LEDs, right?

00:39:14.550 --> 00:39:17.000
But I was rooting for the guys
who made these experiments

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:19.810
with the fundamental
questions of quantum physics,

00:39:19.810 --> 00:39:24.380
in particular can you find
a theory that could describe

00:39:24.380 --> 00:39:26.710
the electron through
local forces?

00:39:26.710 --> 00:39:28.740
You know, that could
explain if it's

00:39:28.740 --> 00:39:30.740
going to spin this
way or that way.

00:39:30.740 --> 00:39:33.430
And what they found out, which
is really an amazing thing,

00:39:33.430 --> 00:39:35.700
is that it's impossible
to build what

00:39:35.700 --> 00:39:38.990
we call a "local theory"
of quantum mechanics

00:39:38.990 --> 00:39:42.440
that explains this
"probability" as the result

00:39:42.440 --> 00:39:46.360
of some fundamental,
underlying causality, right?

00:39:46.360 --> 00:39:49.210
So Einstein was wrong.

00:39:49.210 --> 00:39:52.070
There is no way you can
create a theory that

00:39:52.070 --> 00:39:54.726
explains this basic,
random behavior

00:39:54.726 --> 00:39:56.350
at the fundamental
quantum level, which

00:39:56.350 --> 00:39:58.470
is great for cartography, right?

00:39:58.470 --> 00:40:01.780
I mean, this is going to be the
essence of quantum computers.

00:40:01.780 --> 00:40:06.230
So there is this whole big
quantum information theory

00:40:06.230 --> 00:40:09.180
framework that is emerging
precisely from this.

00:40:09.180 --> 00:40:11.810
But on the other hand, from
this perspective of how much

00:40:11.810 --> 00:40:14.460
can we know of the world,
you have a fundamental block

00:40:14.460 --> 00:40:15.000
right there.

00:40:15.942 --> 00:40:17.650
And finally I just
wanted to make a point

00:40:17.650 --> 00:40:21.650
that this is a quote
from Democritus.

00:40:21.650 --> 00:40:26.160
So he knew all these things,
but he knew also that careful

00:40:26.160 --> 00:40:28.060
when you talk about truth.

00:40:28.060 --> 00:40:31.070
And a lot of scientists,
many colleagues of mine,

00:40:31.070 --> 00:40:34.540
make these big, bold
statements that should not

00:40:34.540 --> 00:40:35.760
be made in public, you know?

00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:40.890
Because sometimes they push what
science really is doing or can

00:40:40.890 --> 00:40:44.300
do way beyond what
we really are doing.

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:47.730
And that is a disservice,
I think, to science,

00:40:47.730 --> 00:40:53.080
especially nowadays when
there is so much criticism

00:40:53.080 --> 00:40:54.560
to what science can do.

00:40:54.560 --> 00:40:57.670
You know, you have all the
global climate deniers, right?

00:40:57.670 --> 00:41:01.250
Who say, oh, these scientists,
they keep changing their minds.

00:41:01.250 --> 00:41:01.890
No, way, look.

00:41:01.890 --> 00:41:03.830
They found gravitational
[INAUDIBLE] from the big bang.

00:41:03.830 --> 00:41:04.330
Right?

00:41:04.330 --> 00:41:09.000
In March there was is big stuff,
actually here in Stanford,

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:09.920
you know?

00:41:09.920 --> 00:41:12.000
I don't know if you guys
know the science people

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:13.620
like Andrei Linde
and all these guys,

00:41:13.620 --> 00:41:16.440
like, there would be Nobel
Prizes all over the place.

00:41:16.440 --> 00:41:18.650
And it's BS, right?

00:41:18.650 --> 00:41:23.180
So they had a press conference
before they had a peer review,

00:41:23.180 --> 00:41:26.110
and that is not what you
should be doing with science.

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:29.219
So that just gives
ammunition to all these guys

00:41:29.219 --> 00:41:31.510
that want to say that we
don't what we're doing, right?

00:41:31.510 --> 00:41:35.490
So the book-- the way I'm
bring this together-- is really

00:41:35.490 --> 00:41:38.230
an effort to bring back
this integrity into science

00:41:38.230 --> 00:41:40.490
and say, look, this
is how we think.

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:43.220
This is how scientific
knowledge is constructed.

00:41:43.220 --> 00:41:47.220
Let's be very careful about
these big, bold statements

00:41:47.220 --> 00:41:49.440
about, yeah, we
understand the big bang.

00:41:49.440 --> 00:41:51.231
We do not understand
the big bang at all.

00:41:51.231 --> 00:41:53.480
You know, there are all sorts
of fundamental questions

00:41:53.480 --> 00:41:55.080
we have no clue about.

00:41:55.080 --> 00:41:57.710
And you have to be very careful,
especially when it's, like,

00:41:57.710 --> 00:42:00.310
Stephen Hawking that
says something like this.

00:42:00.310 --> 00:42:03.825
Anyway, just for the
last couple of minutes,

00:42:03.825 --> 00:42:06.060
I want to talk
about the last part.

00:42:06.060 --> 00:42:07.600
the cognitive part, right?

00:42:07.600 --> 00:42:10.340
And first of all, we have
to say sorry to Descartes

00:42:10.340 --> 00:42:12.590
because there is
no dualism, right?

00:42:12.590 --> 00:42:15.026
There is no matter
and soul, right?

00:42:15.026 --> 00:42:16.890
There is just matter.

00:42:16.890 --> 00:42:19.720
And the big question in
cognitive neuroscience

00:42:19.720 --> 00:42:23.980
is exactly how does
the brain engender you

00:42:23.980 --> 00:42:25.620
with your sense of self, right?

00:42:25.620 --> 00:42:28.650
So you have 85 billion
neurons, they are all

00:42:28.650 --> 00:42:32.722
connected-- which is about the
same as stars in a galaxy which

00:42:32.722 --> 00:42:35.030
is kind of a cute
image-- and they're

00:42:35.030 --> 00:42:38.670
connected to one another by
thousands of synapses, right?

00:42:38.670 --> 00:42:43.000
And the question is, how is
that giving you your ability

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:45.890
to think and to be
yourself every day?

00:42:45.890 --> 00:42:49.230
You wake up the next morning
and you're still you, right?

00:42:49.230 --> 00:42:51.380
There is some sort
of continuity here,

00:42:51.380 --> 00:42:53.554
and we are all made
of the same stuff,

00:42:53.554 --> 00:42:54.720
and yet we are so different.

00:42:56.050 --> 00:42:58.980
So how exactly is that going on?

00:42:58.980 --> 00:43:04.670
So at the bottom of this debate
is really the question can

00:43:04.670 --> 00:43:07.420
we build artificial
intelligence machines, right?

00:43:07.420 --> 00:43:09.960
I mean, is that
something that we can do?

00:43:09.960 --> 00:43:14.629
And the effort for-- the
movement for starting this

00:43:14.629 --> 00:43:15.920
started at Dartmouth, actually.

00:43:15.920 --> 00:43:19.750
In 1956 there was
a conference there

00:43:19.750 --> 00:43:24.190
which started artificial
intelligence communities

00:43:24.190 --> 00:43:25.095
so to speak, right?

00:43:25.095 --> 00:43:27.380
With Marvin Minsky
and Claude Shannon

00:43:27.380 --> 00:43:29.510
and some very smart people.

00:43:29.510 --> 00:43:33.210
And they said, of
course we can build

00:43:33.210 --> 00:43:36.680
a machine that can
think like a human.

00:43:36.680 --> 00:43:39.550
You have to make a distinction
here, one thing is to think.

00:43:39.550 --> 00:43:41.950
The other thing is to
think like a human, meaning

00:43:41.950 --> 00:43:45.560
emulate a human brain
through machines.

00:43:45.560 --> 00:43:48.040
And they were convinced that
was happening real quick,

00:43:48.040 --> 00:43:49.820
it was just a matter
of a few years.

00:43:49.820 --> 00:43:50.960
And here we are, right?

00:43:50.960 --> 00:43:53.530
I mean, you know this
better than I do.

00:43:53.530 --> 00:43:56.020
We have the fastest
computers now

00:43:56.020 --> 00:44:00.200
at about 10 to 16 floating
point operations per second.

00:44:00.200 --> 00:44:03.490
The brain, it is "estimated"--
because we really don't know

00:44:03.490 --> 00:44:06.530
exactly-- at about 10 to 18.

00:44:06.530 --> 00:44:08.170
So we're almost there.

00:44:08.170 --> 00:44:10.870
And this guy called
Henry Markram, who

00:44:10.870 --> 00:44:13.950
got the biggest grant in
the history of science

00:44:13.950 --> 00:44:18.150
for the Human Brain Project
in Europe, 1 billion euros

00:44:18.150 --> 00:44:22.660
to emulate the human brain
in every possible detail,

00:44:22.660 --> 00:44:25.250
says-- or is convinced
that by 2018 we

00:44:25.250 --> 00:44:27.490
will have machines
that will get to the 10

00:44:27.490 --> 00:44:30.050
to 18 floating point operations.

00:44:30.050 --> 00:44:33.470
And so if that's true,
is that all you need?

00:44:33.470 --> 00:44:35.340
That's the real fundamental
question, right?

00:44:35.340 --> 00:44:38.980
Can you just then input
all these 85 billion

00:44:38.980 --> 00:44:40.830
neurons, connect them?

00:44:40.830 --> 00:44:44.510
And they even want to do the
flow of neurotransmitters

00:44:44.510 --> 00:44:45.950
through synapses.

00:44:45.950 --> 00:44:47.450
You know, they
really want to create

00:44:47.450 --> 00:44:49.500
some sort of
hydrodynamic code that

00:44:49.500 --> 00:44:53.340
can mesh with the
sort of binary flip

00:44:53.340 --> 00:44:56.160
on and off from the neurons.

00:44:56.160 --> 00:44:58.191
It's a beautiful,
ambitious project.

00:44:58.191 --> 00:44:59.690
But the question
is can you do that?

00:44:59.690 --> 00:45:04.190
And so well, the problem
behind this-- and there

00:45:04.190 --> 00:45:07.400
is a group of philosophers that
have the best name ever, it's

00:45:07.400 --> 00:45:10.280
called the new
mysterians, right?

00:45:10.280 --> 00:45:13.450
And the new mysterians
say, we can't do that.

00:45:13.450 --> 00:45:17.650
We cannot understand the
human mind and certainly not

00:45:17.650 --> 00:45:19.260
to reconstruct it in a machine.

00:45:19.260 --> 00:45:22.070
You may be able to
reconstruct or create

00:45:22.070 --> 00:45:24.950
some mind, but not
the human mind.

00:45:24.950 --> 00:45:25.450
You know?

00:45:25.450 --> 00:45:28.360
And that's an important
distinction because we cannot

00:45:28.360 --> 00:45:29.750
understand consciousness, right?

00:45:29.750 --> 00:45:33.110
So this is what's called the
hard problem of consciousness

00:45:33.110 --> 00:45:37.510
is the notion that one thing
is to look at a painting

00:45:37.510 --> 00:45:41.600
and monitor all the neurons that
are flashing because you see

00:45:41.600 --> 00:45:44.760
the painting and you react
to the painting emotionally.

00:45:44.760 --> 00:45:48.880
The other thing is to understand
the subjective experience

00:45:48.880 --> 00:45:50.605
of what it means to
look at the painting.

00:45:50.605 --> 00:45:52.890
They are two different things.

00:45:52.890 --> 00:45:55.930
There is a disconnect
between the two things.

00:45:55.930 --> 00:45:57.825
And also another
way of saying it

00:45:57.825 --> 00:45:59.394
is that when I
look at a painting,

00:45:59.394 --> 00:46:00.810
and you look at a
painting, we are

00:46:00.810 --> 00:46:02.280
going to see the
same information.

00:46:02.280 --> 00:46:03.600
Like, there is a
painting, right?

00:46:03.600 --> 00:46:05.766
But I'm going to react in
a very different way from,

00:46:05.766 --> 00:46:08.340
because I have
this consciousness

00:46:08.340 --> 00:46:12.380
and this subjective experience,
which is not the same as yours.

00:46:12.380 --> 00:46:16.200
Which a third way of thinking
is that the brain cannot figure

00:46:16.200 --> 00:46:18.460
itself out, right?

00:46:18.460 --> 00:46:22.300
And no computer simulation
can simulate itself

00:46:22.300 --> 00:46:25.630
or include itself in
the simulation, right?

00:46:25.630 --> 00:46:27.700
And that's a problem in
computer science, right?

00:46:27.700 --> 00:46:30.320
I mean, you cannot have a
computer simulation that

00:46:30.320 --> 00:46:33.810
includes the computer in
the simulation itself.

00:46:33.810 --> 00:46:37.850
So we have a hard one,
essentially, here, right?

00:46:37.850 --> 00:46:41.360
And that is the third
dimension, and of course I

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:43.430
couldn't come here
and not mention

00:46:43.430 --> 00:46:47.220
that this issue of--
the question of living

00:46:47.220 --> 00:46:49.040
in a simulation
or not is actually

00:46:49.040 --> 00:46:52.230
a very serious,
complicated question.

00:46:52.230 --> 00:46:55.240
And we cannot know, right
now, if we are living

00:46:55.240 --> 00:46:57.170
in a simulation or not, right?

00:46:57.170 --> 00:47:00.640
There was a paper last
year from some colleagues

00:47:00.640 --> 00:47:05.090
that they said that if our--
if we are a simulation,

00:47:05.090 --> 00:47:08.190
and they use a lattice to
simulate reality, which is,

00:47:08.190 --> 00:47:11.100
say, a square lattice, for
example a cubic lattice,

00:47:11.100 --> 00:47:12.430
to be three dimensional.

00:47:12.430 --> 00:47:14.340
Every lattice, when
you simulate something,

00:47:14.340 --> 00:47:16.360
has a spatial resolution.

00:47:16.360 --> 00:47:19.430
And in order to probe
very short distances,

00:47:19.430 --> 00:47:22.460
you can shoot particles
at very high energies

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:24.820
to probe these distances
so it is, in principle,

00:47:24.820 --> 00:47:28.940
possible to tell what would
be the spatial resolution

00:47:28.940 --> 00:47:32.610
of the lattice that is
simulating us, right?

00:47:32.610 --> 00:47:35.020
Because the aliens,
or whoever they are,

00:47:35.020 --> 00:47:39.810
would need to save memory
by doing this lattice.

00:47:39.810 --> 00:47:41.620
No lattice is
infinitely thin, right?

00:47:41.620 --> 00:47:44.710
You have to cut off at
some spatial resolution.

00:47:44.710 --> 00:47:48.636
And so, you know, the
point being here well,

00:47:48.636 --> 00:47:50.010
but, you know, if
it's very fine,

00:47:50.010 --> 00:47:51.840
it's way beyond
anything that we could

00:47:51.840 --> 00:47:55.440
create right now in terms
of energy say at the LHC.

00:47:55.440 --> 00:47:58.411
So we could be fooled, and
it's a really hard question

00:47:58.411 --> 00:47:58.910
to answer.

00:47:58.910 --> 00:48:00.260
Sort of like the Sims, right?

00:48:00.260 --> 00:48:02.756
Think of the Sims
50 years from now.

00:48:03.990 --> 00:48:06.000
And we know that we
are playing the Sims,

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:08.480
and they have absolutely
no autonomy, right?

00:48:08.480 --> 00:48:11.300
But 50 years from now, you can
imagine that SIM characters are

00:48:11.300 --> 00:48:14.160
going to be so developed and
so self-sufficient they're

00:48:14.160 --> 00:48:17.790
going to believe that their
autonomous those individuals.

00:48:17.790 --> 00:48:20.710
So they will believe
that they are real.

00:48:20.710 --> 00:48:22.570
And, you know, our
grandkids or whatever

00:48:22.570 --> 00:48:26.000
will be playing with them,
and they aren't, right?

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:27.030
But they don't know.

00:48:27.030 --> 00:48:29.400
So the question is can we know?

00:48:29.400 --> 00:48:31.560
And that is the other
complicated question.

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:34.950
So just to wrap up
what is this notion

00:48:34.950 --> 00:48:36.590
of the island of knowledge then?

00:48:36.590 --> 00:48:39.430
Well, it's the way we really
construct scientific knowledge,

00:48:39.430 --> 00:48:39.930
right?

00:48:39.930 --> 00:48:41.910
So you have an
island, which is where

00:48:41.910 --> 00:48:44.700
you put all your knowledge, and
this island can change in time.

00:48:44.700 --> 00:48:46.710
It can grow, as we
understand things.

00:48:46.710 --> 00:48:48.960
Sometimes it shrinks,
like the aether, right?

00:48:48.960 --> 00:48:51.820
And it would be all jagged
because things are not linear.

00:48:51.820 --> 00:48:54.500
But there is an island that
is on the average growing,

00:48:54.500 --> 00:48:57.170
and it's surrounded by this
ocean of the unknown, the stuff

00:48:57.170 --> 00:48:58.980
that we don't know
about the world.

00:48:58.980 --> 00:49:01.520
And the idea then is
there are two ways, right?

00:49:01.520 --> 00:49:04.430
So the native people would say,
hey, the island of knowledge

00:49:04.430 --> 00:49:05.760
grows, grows, grows.

00:49:05.760 --> 00:49:08.390
And eventually there is not
going to be anymore unknown.

00:49:08.390 --> 00:49:09.580
It's the end of science.

00:49:09.580 --> 00:49:11.230
A lot of people
talked about this.

00:49:11.230 --> 00:49:13.120
And that is complete
nonsense, right?

00:49:13.120 --> 00:49:15.960
Because, as I try
to explain here,

00:49:15.960 --> 00:49:19.730
as the island of
knowledge grows so does

00:49:19.730 --> 00:49:21.670
the shore of our
ignorance, which

00:49:21.670 --> 00:49:24.550
is the boundary between the
known and the unknown, which

00:49:24.550 --> 00:49:27.380
basically means this
as we know more,

00:49:27.380 --> 00:49:30.300
we become equipped
to ask questions

00:49:30.300 --> 00:49:32.340
that we couldn't have
contemplated before.

00:49:33.470 --> 00:49:36.450
Going back to the example
of the microscope, right?

00:49:36.450 --> 00:49:39.640
Nobody could have
predicted that life

00:49:39.640 --> 00:49:42.790
would have been that small
before the instrument opened

00:49:42.790 --> 00:49:45.050
a completely different
reality to people

00:49:45.050 --> 00:49:47.570
and allowed people to
ask more questions.

00:49:47.570 --> 00:49:49.970
So the notion of
final truth, which

00:49:49.970 --> 00:49:52.770
implies complete
knowledge, is absurd

00:49:52.770 --> 00:49:55.530
because you can never
ask all questions.

00:49:57.090 --> 00:49:59.114
So if you can't ask all
questions, how the heck

00:49:59.114 --> 00:50:00.280
do you know all the answers?

00:50:00.280 --> 00:50:02.390
Which is a much harder
thing to do, right?

00:50:02.390 --> 00:50:05.070
So that's the essential idea.

00:50:05.070 --> 00:50:08.420
And so you have this
map over there, right?

00:50:08.420 --> 00:50:11.250
And you have these unknowables
that I mentioned briefly here,

00:50:11.250 --> 00:50:11.750
right?

00:50:11.750 --> 00:50:13.920
So to take this
into contect, it's

00:50:13.920 --> 00:50:17.094
not like, oh, damn, this is
such a defeatist kind of idea,

00:50:17.094 --> 00:50:18.135
because it isn't, really.

00:50:18.135 --> 00:50:22.150
It's really about how we make
meaning in the world, right?

00:50:22.150 --> 00:50:25.030
We are always trying to
go beyond our limits,

00:50:25.030 --> 00:50:27.120
and that's exactly
what it should be.

00:50:27.120 --> 00:50:30.150
And it's really searching
that makes us matter.

00:50:30.150 --> 00:50:32.750
It is wanting to know that
gives us value, you know?

00:50:32.750 --> 00:50:36.170
It's trying to find the
meaning that gives us

00:50:36.170 --> 00:50:39.670
value, not necessarily arriving
at the end of everything.

00:50:39.670 --> 00:50:46.560
And so to conclude, from the
way I picture things here,

00:50:46.560 --> 00:50:51.310
what we call reality is really
a shifting map of ideas.

00:50:51.310 --> 00:50:55.290
Because, as you've seen, the
fundamental core of reality

00:50:55.290 --> 00:50:59.610
has changed as our knowledge
of nature has changed in time.

00:50:59.610 --> 00:51:01.580
And there is no
reason to believe

00:51:01.580 --> 00:51:04.040
that that's not going
to continue, right?

00:51:04.040 --> 00:51:06.130
So we can talk about
what we know now

00:51:06.130 --> 00:51:08.920
and what we knew
before, but not saying

00:51:08.920 --> 00:51:10.760
that this is the
end of the story.

00:51:10.760 --> 00:51:14.510
This is just one beginning, and
there'll be many, many others.

00:51:14.510 --> 00:51:15.557
And that's it.

00:51:15.557 --> 00:51:16.390
Thank you very much.

